Hi friends =E2=80=8B=E2=80=8B=F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Thursday! I hope those of you in the US had a great 4th of July weeke=
nd, and that the rest of you enjoyed a peaceful extra day away from your Am=
erican colleagues.=20
I thought the patriotic holiday would be the perfect time to look at the hi=
story and future of deeptech innovation in the United States. I believe tha=
t after two decades of pure software (bits) dominating the startup landscap=
e, we=E2=80=99re entering a golden age for atoms. Today, Not Boring Researc=
h Analyst Rahul Rana [https://substack.com/redirect/c6436659-9623-4d52-81c2=
-c5417e4125b7?u=3D16283549] is going to explain what=E2=80=99s driving that=
, which categories are most promising, and why we need more moonshots.=20
A few weeks ago, I introduced you to Elliot Hershberg [https://substack.com=
/redirect/2cea22ff-f5f0-4e04-a796-f05d08c905d7?u=3D16283549], our Research =
Analyst focused on biotech, when he wrote about Ginkgo Bioworks [https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/02616188-b4ab-4c4d-b9e7-331ffd1d1319?u=3D16283549]. I t=
old you that I=E2=80=99d introduce you to Rahul soon. Today is that day.  =20
Rahul is a force. A rising senior double-majoring in finance and astrophysi=
cs, Rahul spent a year interning at Lux Capital followed by many months bui=
lding Arcadia Science while in school and writing a book, Making Moonshots =
[https://substack.com/redirect/6cead4a4-2047-4e77-a15a-27c49c956fe3?u=3D162=
83549]. This summer, in addition to joining Not Boring to focus on deeptech=
, Rahul is interning at the $84 billion growth giant, General Atlantic.=20
From working with the best investors in the space, and literally writing th=
e book on the subject, Rahul has a deep understanding of what it takes to m=
ake moonshots.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
Making Moonshots
Part 1: Schemes of Cosmic Magnitude
After decades of government-led scientific progress, the time has come for =
deeptech startups to lead the charge. These startups will lean on academic =
research and governments, tapping into their vast budgets and real needs. B=
ut the pieces are in place for deeptech startups to drive the innovation ag=
enda.=C2=A0
My thesis: deeptech startups are just as important as academia to scientifi=
c progress.
Research offers the foundational knowledge that startups scale to the gener=
al public. We need both=E2=80=94academia and industry=E2=80=94there=E2=80=
=99s no question about it. But tracing back to World War II, one of the mos=
t significant turning points in American ingenuity, public funding and dire=
ction were practically required for large-scale scientific progress. Today,=
 America needs to lean on its competitive advantage=E2=80=93bottoms-up inno=
vation=E2=80=93to win the next century.=C2=A0
For the past 70 years, when it came to deeptech and scientific progress, th=
e government led,=C2=A0 and then handed off to the public sector to commerc=
ialize technology beyond military applications. The Manhattan Project, for =
example, directly created the atomic bomb and indirectly unlocked insights =
that made nuclear power possible. Today, nuclear is a crucial element of en=
ergy abundance and a potent weapon in the fight against climate change. Iro=
nically, the atomic bomb could help save or destroy the planet.
Military R&D around nuclear physics also advanced our understanding of biol=
ogy with the popularization of radioisotopes as treatments for cancer, diag=
nostics, and tools [https://substack.com/redirect/c0a4327f-fca2-4fb4-8508-3=
b5e60ddb6b6?u=3D16283549] for understanding metabolic pathways. War efforts=
 even birthed the first general-purpose computer, the ENIAC, by way of cryp=
tography used to decipher German military codes.=C2=A0
The War sparked a period known as the Era of Big Science [https://substack.=
com/redirect/5f7f6177-3084-491a-9caa-01e1d623c791?u=3D16283549], characteri=
zed by large-scale projects usually funded by national governments or group=
s of governments. At the time, over a decade before Arthur Rock wrote a ven=
ture check into Fairchild Semiconductor, federal, top-down coordination and=
 money were necessary for the sheer scale of the projects at hand. Without =
the government=E2=80=99s direct intervention, we probably would not have be=
en able to fight the AIDS epidemic, rally against cancer, lay the beginning=
s of the internet, or even discover fundamental concepts of biology, chemis=
try, and physics=E2=80=94such as the discovery of the DNA double helix, MRI=
 machines, and the bulk of modern astrophysics.=C2=A0
These giant leaps in science trace back to one hero: Vannevar Bush. As the =
globe marched toward inevitable world war, it was clear to him that the mil=
itary technology of the past would be rendered obsolete by the enemy=E2=80=
=99s arsenal. Science had a vital role to play in turning the tide of the w=
ar toward the Allied Powers, but understanding that wasn=E2=80=99t intuitiv=
e to the government at the time.=C2=A0
Enter Bush [https://substack.com/redirect/f91d420b-6a41-4a8a-b370-e01c2e262=
667?u=3D16283549]: a professor at MIT and inventor of the differential anal=
yzer [https://substack.com/redirect/8826c6d4-c2c4-40a3-a254-53dcbed0bc31?u=
=3D16283549], one of the first operational computing mechanisms. Bush was a=
n ardent proponent of deeptech as a means of winning the war because he saw=
 first-hand the shortcomings [https://substack.com/redirect/5b58a269-667d-4=
602-864a-c83a232876ed?u=3D16283549] of government and academic research aft=
er WWI as the Dean of Engineering and VP of MIT. Before Germany invaded Pol=
and, he left his post to establish a national emphasis on research in Washi=
ngton, DC as the Director of the National Advisory Committee on Aeronautics=
=2E After the invasion, the urgency of hi=
s mission became more apparent. Bush=
 took on the prodigious task of convincing President Franklin Delano Roosev=
elt to invest in science, not just weapons of mass destruction, but the end=
less frontier that would hold the keys to a sustainable victory. Surprising=
ly, it worked.=C2=A0
In 1940, the National Defense Research Committee was created to boost defen=
se industries. About a year later, Bush chaired the Office of Scientific Re=
search and Development. Under his leadership, fundamental research took pla=
ce around things we now take for granted: rocketry, radar, sonar, and more.=
=C2=A0
As the War ended, Roosevelt consulted Bush about what the country should do=
 to take full advantage of the industrial complex built up in support of th=
e military effort. =E2=80=9CThere is,=E2=80=9D the President wrote, =E2=80=
=9Cno reason why the lessons to be found in this experiment cannot be profi=
tably employed in times of peace.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
You can find President Roosevelt=E2=80=99s famed letter here [https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/4424c1a2-ac1e-466e-ad81-0cccccd302e4?u=3D16283549]. In sum=
mary, he asked Bush four questions:=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CWhat can be done, consistent with military security, and with the =
prior approval of the military authorities, to make known to the world as s=
oon as possible the contributions which have been made during our war effor=
t to scientific knowledge?=E2=80=9D
=E2=80=9CWith particular reference to the war of science against disease, w=
hat can be done now to organize a program for continuing in the future the =
work which has been done in medicine and related sciences?=E2=80=9D
=E2=80=9CWhat can the Government do now and in the future to aid research a=
ctivities by public and private organizations? The proper roles of public a=
nd of private research, and their interrelation, should be carefully consid=
ered.=E2=80=9D
=E2=80=9CCan an effective program be proposed for discovering and developin=
g scientific talent in American youth so that the continuing future of scie=
ntific research in this country may be assured on a level comparable to wha=
t has been done during the war?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Bush replied with his renowned Science, the Endless Frontier [https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/4424c1a2-ac1e-466e-ad81-0cccccd302e4?u=3D16283549] essay, =
which laid out his proposed solutions. In summary: invest in science and ta=
ke out the economic and structural riskiness in pursuing R&D breakthroughs =
while ensuring the well-being of these pioneers, revitalizing research cult=
ure, and developing talent.=C2=A0
He declared that =E2=80=9Cscience can be effective in the national welfare =
only as a member of a team, whether the conditions be peace or war. But wit=
hout scientific progress no amount of achievement in other directions can i=
nsure our health, prosperity, and security as a nation in the modern world.=
=E2=80=9D It was simple. An enduring civilization was nothing without advan=
ces in how it gets things done. Stagnation meant death.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Bush=E2=80=99s objectives were reminiscent of American policy more broadly.=
 Historically, it has been the purview of the government to tackle new fron=
tiers=E2=80=94the West, then Alaska, then outer space. The same goes for te=
chnological progress. Over the years, the government established generation=
al institutions such as NASA, DARPA, and ARPA-E to solve formidable problem=
s and make discoveries. They also established a plethora of bureaucratic fu=
nding mechanisms that award the most innovative projects: Small Business In=
novation Research (SBIR), National Science Foundation (NSF), and many other=
s. Executive branch departments and entire university systems uphold the sa=
me goals.=C2=A0
By the 1960s, the military-industrial complex became the scientific-industr=
ial complex as US military-funded R&D came to represent 30% [https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/d39a1ba1-6de4-4127-92bb-cd53ac0a5e2d?u=3D16283549] of all R=
&D worldwide. The military provided 50% [https://substack.com/redirect/d39a=
1ba1-6de4-4127-92bb-cd53ac0a5e2d?u=3D16283549] of all university R&D dollar=
s and 25% [https://substack.com/redirect/d39a1ba1-6de4-4127-92bb-cd53ac0a5e=
2d?u=3D16283549] of corporate R&D dollars.=C2=A0
However, this trend started flipping in the 70s and 80 [https://substack.co=
m/redirect/1b470f8e-879e-4fe0-850f-83f5aef8b3ad?u=3D16283549]s. Government =
legislation, such as the 1980 Bayh-Dole Act [https://substack.com/redirect/=
c512ae6f-7093-40f8-adb5-7aca677f58b8?u=3D16283549], which formed patent pro=
tection for publicly-funded research, allowed the commercialization of the =
vast pool of scientific and technological knowledge we had accumulated over=
 the previous four decades. As a result, the productivity of private enterp=
rises outpaced that of federally-funded research as a percentage of GDP.=C2=
=A0
This shift fueled a culture war between private and public R&D. In 1983, fo=
llowing the Bell System Divestiture, employees of Bell Labs encapsulated th=
is sentiment in a quote [https://substack.com/redirect/bd4db705-f260-40b7-a=
ec9-4bb0c0b74367?u=3D16283549]:=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThere are two giant entities at work in our country, and they both=
 have an amazing influence on our daily lives... one has given us radar, so=
nar, stereo, teletype, the transistor, hearing aids, artificial larynxes, t=
alking movies, and the telephone. The other has given us the Civil War, the=
 Spanish American War, the First World War, the Second World War, the Korea=
n War, the Vietnam War, double-digit inflation, double-digit unemployment, =
the Great Depression, the gasoline crisis, and the Watergate fiasco. Guess =
which one is now trying to tell the other one how to run its business?=E2=
=80=9D
Despite the government=E2=80=99s attempts to tell the commercial sector =E2=
=80=9Chow to run its business,=E2=80=9D regulations could not stop the marc=
h of commercial American dynamism. Privately owned deeptech companies could=
 bring their learnings from lab to market. Teledyne [https://substack.com/r=
edirect/ce4a329d-eb61-4d89-b0c8-d1f9b864683c?u=3D16283549], Genentech [http=
s://substack.com/redirect/bfb51199-6e84-411a-862f-af1cd4c0763f?u=3D16283549=
], Intel [https://substack.com/redirect/583b783a-153f-4f8d-9c91-7c45e5db7cf=
0?u=3D16283549], and Apple [https://substack.com/redirect/e56050c3-51fd-492=
9-81b3-59d975ba0f5b?u=3D16283549] were born during this initial wave, launc=
hing a new era of progress. Inspirational stories of scientists unintention=
ally making ground-breaking realizations became those of founders risk-taki=
ng their way into ambitious startups.=C2=A0
It's popular to point out that America doesn't build like we used to=E2=80=
=94during WW2, the Space Race, or even the 1970s, when Apple and Genentech =
were both founded in the year of our nation's Bicentennial. Something happe=
ned around 1973; progress slowed. We lost our ambition. As Jeff Hammerbache=
r [https://substack.com/redirect/5902f54b-5e9c-4aa8-91c4-b028d8f6edef?u=3D1=
6283549] complained, "the best minds of my generation are thinking about ho=
w to make people click ads." I=E2=80=99d argue that it was because we saw a=
 divergence in private-public collaboration as the government focused on ot=
her domestic issues.
Neil deGrasse Tyson says it best in his 2012 speech, We Stopped Dreaming:
But that narrative is stale. The dreaming is here; it=E2=80=99s just not ev=
enly distributed.
Today, a new wave of truly awe-inspiring companies are pushing the frontier=
s of what=E2=80=99s possible. The argument that capital markets lack the in=
centive to pursue scientific risk is a fallacy: commercial space companies =
are researching and productizing 3-D printed rockets and space infrastructu=
re (Relativity Space [https://substack.com/redirect/636483a6-03ac-439d-99ac=
-a614e3e570da?u=3D16283549]); biotech startups are discovering drugs and bu=
ilding scalable platforms to expedite the process (Enveda Biosciences [http=
s://substack.com/redirect/d90f2f9b-bc8e-49b7-835b-8dbb4eef5135?u=3D16283549=
]); energy ventures are profitably fighting climate change (Tesla [https://=
substack.com/redirect/847d1f8e-3e83-45aa-9017-8040cde79e54?u=3D16283549]). =
These are just a few areas where societal progress is led by private indust=
ry - deeptech companies across the spectrum are taking on society's toughes=
t challenges.
Scientific progress is now distributed amongst thousands of venture-backed =
entrepreneurial scientists that are collectively iterating and advancing th=
eir fields in a financially sustainable way.=C2=A0
When thinking about how science was and is done in the USA, the overall tre=
nd follows a yin-and-yang relationship between public and private R&D. Howe=
ver, given the current state of the nation, only cohesive collaboration bet=
ween public and private will lead to the outcomes we need.=C2=A0
We need more people to start dreaming again. We need more startups that sol=
ve seemingly impossible problems and change the course of history=E2=80=94t=
hose that have =E2=80=9Cschemes of cosmic magnitude [https://substack.com/r=
edirect/55b6d550-505e-49de-93ec-e2a7133af8c6?u=3D16283549].=E2=80=9D One mo=
re successful moonshot has the potential to drastically reduce any aspect o=
f human suffering and pull us out of the stagnation we face. One more moons=
hot can push the course of technological progress and societal progress, in=
 turn bringing forth a new golden age. A movement starts with one.=C2=A0
When something previously thought of as inconceivable becomes a reality, it=
 spurs action at the individual and collective levels. New companies build =
off of the prior generation=E2=80=99s innovations, widening the scope of wh=
o can create deeptech companies. Innovation becomes infrastructure, infrast=
ructure becomes a launch pad. From geeks to polymaths, everyone has an esse=
ntial role in invention and innovation.
We need moonshots.=C2=A0
Part 2: To The Moon
We need more moonshot companies: bold startups that leverage a frontier tec=
hnology or science to solve an exigent problem in the world. Not another ad=
 optimization tool. Or yet another zero-utility NFT project. I=E2=80=99m ta=
lking about those like Moderna [https://substack.com/redirect/d6a931e0-ad66=
-42af-8b84-fb4a9faec543?u=3D16283549], which is containing an entire pandem=
ic with RNA vaccines, or Commonwealth Fusion [https://substack.com/redirect=
/cd224e11-22eb-4fd8-9c72-75dd1eee41c5?u=3D16283549], which is commercializi=
ng fusion energy.=C2=A0
The term =E2=80=9CMoonshot=E2=80=9D was born out of the Apollo Missions, sp=
ecifically Apollo 11, which put the first man on the Moon in 1969. I know P=
acky has shared the famous JFK =E2=80=9CWe Choose to Go to the Moon=E2=80=
=9D speech before, but I=E2=80=99m going to share it again. Watch it.=C2=A0
I love the Apollo story because of what happened at the nexus of two branch=
es. One branch was the private-public sector collaboration between NASA and=
 universities, namely MIT. The second one starts with Nobel Prize winner Wi=
lliam Shockley of Bell Labs, who invented the transistor in 1947 and founde=
d Shockley Semiconductor in 1955. As a key figure within the computing indu=
stry, Shockley was widely known and attracted incredible talent, but his bi=
tter management style turned off some of the scientists he hired. There wer=
e seven notable ones.=C2=A0
Enter Arthur Rock, the legendary godfather of Silicon Valley. Rock serendip=
itously met some of those scientists disheartened by Shockley=E2=80=99s lea=
dership. Instead of getting them hired at another firm, he pushed them to s=
tart their own company. The group of seven added one more scientist as per =
a recommendation from Rock and accordingly became =E2=80=9CThe Traitorous E=
ight.=E2=80=9D Their company agreed with the existing Fairchild Camera and =
Instrument to establish a semiconductor arm, which became Fairchild Semicon=
ductor. An industry giant was born.=C2=A0
Now, the two branches link together, as publicly-funded NASA and MIT needed=
 advanced computing measures for their systems=E2=80=94specifically integra=
ted circuits. The Apollo Missions became one of privately-funded Fairchild =
Semiconductor=E2=80=99s most important early customers, despite its technol=
ogy being extremely novel and untested on a massive scale. NASA provided a =
much-needed stress test for Fairchild, as integrated circuits were painfull=
y quality-tested. They needed to be perfect. The weight of the Apollo missi=
ons rested on Fairchild=E2=80=99s technology. It was a daunting task.=C2=A0
But, as (almost) always, innovation pulled through. NASA and MIT asked, and=
 Fairchild executed, making chips that skyrocketed computing power, reliabi=
lity, and memory by nearly 1,000 times. To articulate the new trend Fairchi=
ld kicked off, Intel co-founder Gordon Moore, the theorist behind Moore=E2=
=80=99s Law, coined the exponential concept explicitly based on NASA=E2=80=
=99s operations. It was the perfect environment to study the rise of comput=
ational power in a real-world setting.
The rest is history. Apollo 11 was a success. The US=E2=80=94its government=
, institutions, and private companies=E2=80=94completed the first moonshot:=
 a crewed lunar landing that returned to earth. The impossible was impossib=
le no more. Fairchild Semiconductor went on to become a generational compan=
y whose employees went on to continue the legacy by founding companies like=
 Intel and AMD.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s not all. One of the most powerful consequences of the Apollo=
 Missions was their effect on regular people. NASA=E2=80=99s founding and s=
pace-related efforts were driven out of fear of Russia=E2=80=99s progress t=
oward the moon. Yet, JFK masterfully channeled this through his famous Moon=
 Speech in a way that galvanized the general public to support the lofty go=
al and dream of the future that they could participate in. People wanted to=
 become scientists and engineers. People wanted economic and social progres=
s. It was the mindset that the space program brought upon us=E2=80=94this f=
eeling of dynamic, cautious optimism=E2=80=94that likely changed the entrep=
reneurship landscape in America.=C2=A0
The imaginative and ambitious startup culture, the cutting-edge breakthroug=
hs, and the resounding, captivating impact of it all=E2=80=94that is what a=
 moonshot is.=C2=A0
Today, a new generation of moonshot companies share the same ethos, but the=
 process has changed. Private companies identify opportunities, marry them =
with applications of cutting-edge research, and then sell to the government=
 and industry. They take risks and build defensible companies, not because =
they are easy, but because they are hard.=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0
Take Kurion [https://substack.com/redirect/c0247847-93b0-4212-87cc-8004ad6f=
60fd?u=3D16283549], a nuclear waste management company founded in 2008 by G=
aetan Bonhomme, John Raymont, and Josh Wolfe.=C2=A0
When everyone was chasing solar energy, ethanol, and biofuels, the team loo=
ked toward advancements in energy that no one was looking at=E2=80=94nuclea=
r power. The team considered the ever-increasing world population and econo=
mic growth, which foretold an inevitable increase in demand for energy. The=
y asked, =E2=80=9CWhat sources of energy would people realistically use in =
the future, how could we contribute to more available, less expensive optio=
ns, and where is there an opportunity to build a profitable business?=E2=80=
=9D
Expert interviews, scientific research, and intelligence reports pointed to=
 harnessing nuclear energy. Yet, they realized that the waste created as a =
byproduct of nuclear operations, whether bomb-making or reactors, was holdi=
ng the industry back. What do we do with the waste? How can we clean it up?=
 What if another Chernobyl happened?=C2=A0
Wolfe found [https://substack.com/redirect/6d59ce4f-410d-496e-a30a-35e4352e=
f632?u=3D16283549] that =E2=80=9C$1 of every $4 spent by the US Department =
of Energy spent wasn=E2=80=99t on =E2=80=98green tech=E2=80=99 but nuclear =
waste cleanup=E2=80=94$6 billion a year,=E2=80=9D and that =E2=80=9Csuch cl=
eanups could take 50 years or more to complete.=E2=80=9D At the time, it co=
st tens of billions of dollars to properly clean up and dispose of nuclear =
waste, and it was found that =E2=80=9Chundreds of billions of dollars will =
be spent globally for decades to come=E2=80=9D if nuclear waste management =
was not solved. With that in mind, Kurion invented a vitrification process =
to lower the lifecycle cost of nuclear waste management by isolating the ra=
dioactive components of the remains and encasing it in a stable formation o=
f geological glass.
Then, Kurion got its big break=E2=80=94a total black swan event.=C2=A0
March 11, 2011. A 9.0 magnitude undersea earthquake shocked Japan and gener=
ated a massive tsunami that obliterated the Japanese shore. Homes, business=
es, roads, and more were wiped out, and to make matters worse, the power su=
pply and cooling systems of the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear power plant were =
disabled. No one had seen it coming; most could only look on in horror.=C2=
=A0
Kurion was prepared. It was one of a few companies selected to collaborate =
with various governments and help contain the waste. In little time, they s=
uccessfully designed, built, and delivered their technology to remove 68 mi=
llion gallons of radioactive waste at a fraction of the previously perceive=
d cost. It was a win for progress and a saving grace for people in Japan.=
=C2=A0
Kurion is a story of defying the odds and fundamentally pushing forward our=
 understanding of chemistry and physics. All done by a team of entrepreneur=
s, bottoms-up. It would have been too late if the team had waited for the g=
overnment to demand a solution. Ideate, innovate, then sell. In the end, Ku=
rion was acquired [https://substack.com/redirect/6a6938b6-0d5b-47b8-b019-fe=
4841bb8765?u=3D16283549] for $350 million in 2016.=C2=A0
We chase moonshots because they fix inefficiencies, drive progress, and mak=
e money. They're still businesses; both the technology and the economics ne=
ed to work. But, the seemingly impossible journey and real-world impact of =
it all is what makes them worthy of the lunar metaphor.=C2=A0
I can keep going.=C2=A0
Imagine devoting your life=E2=80=99s work to unearthing a fairly complex co=
ncept within neuroscience and even getting a principle named after you, the=
n having that work almost entirely invalidated by a newcomer to the space.=
=C2=A0
That sucks.=C2=A0
This is exactly what happened to neurophysiologist Elwood Henneman. The Hen=
neman Size Principle states that in motor recruitment, the neurons that con=
trol muscles act in groups according to the magnitude of the force needed f=
or an action. Essentially, it was believed you could not turn individual ne=
urons on or off, that you can only fire off a group of them with the number=
 determined by a movement=E2=80=99s strength.=C2=A0
Founder Thomas Reardon and his team at CTRL Labs disproved that principle [=
https://substack.com/redirect/7417ab68-89f9-4285-bfa1-6eea53f34d4c?u=3D1628=
3549] by building a noninvasive hardware solution that connects one=E2=80=
=99s nervous system to a computer or machine=E2=80=94effectively allowing a=
 user to control the machine with an intent to act. Upon isolating each fir=
ed neuron, the signal that would go to a muscle can be translated and expre=
ssed on a brain-computer interface. Yes, CTRL Labs made mind-control a real=
ity.
Think of the Force in Star Wars. By merely thinking about a certain action,=
 those who can wield the Force can control an external entity=E2=80=94wheth=
er it=E2=80=99s an object or an entire person. Reardon figured out a way to=
 =E2=80=9Cescape the boundaries of your body=E2=80=9D by fundamentally gran=
ting a user more control over their life.=C2=A0
His motivation [https://substack.com/redirect/d171c5cc-f5e8-4fde-8c5b-726f2=
2a2a565?u=3D16283549]?=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99m working on human happiness. I=E2=80=99m working on empowering p=
eople. I=E2=80=99m working on giving people new, extraordinary abilities...=
 I didn=E2=80=99t want to create technology that was for 100,000 people or =
a million people. I wanted to create technology that was for 8 billion peop=
le.
While he wants to prove the =E2=80=9Cimpossible=E2=80=9D is possible and bu=
ild a high-leverage project, Reardon=E2=80=99s motivating force is giving p=
eople autonomy. That=E2=80=99s quite fitting, considering that he made Inte=
rnet Explorer in the 1990s [https://substack.com/redirect/64840123-2675-400=
d-965d-1ae103d72bb4?u=3D16283549]. He knows how to impact and empower a bil=
lion people=E2=80=94in typical moonshot fashion. It=E2=80=99s also worth no=
ting that only four years after its founding in 2015, Facebook acquired CTR=
L Labs for $1 billion. In the 2021 event, The Metaverse And How We=E2=80=99=
ll Build It Together [https://substack.com/redirect/f48fee84-d1b2-4e94-8481=
-3582e323668c?u=3D16283549], the rechristened Meta showed off CTRL-Lab=E2=
=80=99s tech in the section titled =E2=80=9CWhat will it take to make the M=
etaverse feel real?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
With Meta=E2=80=99s nearly 3 billion monthly active users, Reardon is nearl=
y halfway to his goal of reaching everybody on the planet.=C2=A0
These modern moonshot institutions aren=E2=80=99t some elusive, once-in-a-l=
ifetime, government-resource-scale thing. They=E2=80=99re tough, and they o=
ften fail, but any such company can cause a paradigm shift in scientific un=
derstanding, actualize the potential to benefit billions, and monetize the =
breakthrough.=C2=A0
Part 3: How to Make a Moonshot
I wrote my book, Making Moonshots [https://substack.com/redirect/a8404d67-4=
88c-4fd8-bd02-1abf77e2afe3?u=3D16283549], to understand the mindsets, philo=
sophies, strategies, and ecosystems conducive to building such ambitious, w=
orld-changing companies.=C2=A0
My goal was and remains simple: to inspire at least one more person to take=
 on such a venture. This has been a passion of mine for years as I grew up =
with two core influences. My father is an engineer who has worked at the hi=
storic Bell Labs my entire life, and my mother is a survivor of 9/11 as she=
 worked in the Twin Towers during that event (the North Tower to be specifi=
c). With those dual influences, I grew up wanting to use science and tech t=
o do good for our country and the world. My book is a manifesto for that.=
=C2=A0
In writing the book, I learned some useful lessons for people who are found=
ing and funding frontier tech and hard sciences ventures.
First, I explored common characteristics among moonshot founders.
Moonshot founders are radically creative. They balance inner contradictions=
, which F. Scott Fitzgerald encapsulated in his quote: =E2=80=9CThe test of=
 a first-rate intelligence is the ability to hold two opposed ideas in mind=
 at the same time and still retain the ability to function.=E2=80=9D
These founders are cautiously optimistic and realistically unrealistic. The=
y are passionately dispassionate, responsibly irresponsible, and pragmatica=
lly impractical.=C2=A0
Interestingly enough, Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi, famed psychologist of the th=
eory of the =E2=80=9Cflow state,=E2=80=9D described creative people in his =
book Creativity: Flow and the Psychology of Discovery and Invention [https:=
//substack.com/redirect/469eba1a-0961-45b4-8c8c-eaf626158f84?u=3D16283549] =
as those who are energetic yet calm; wise yet naive; playful yet discipline=
d; extroverted yet introverted; humble yet proud; traditional & conservativ=
e yet rebellious & iconoclastic.=C2=A0
Csikszentmihalyi narrowed his research down to those ten traits from a samp=
le of nearly 100 people legendary in their respective fields=E2=80=94includ=
ing fourteen Nobel Prize winners, musicians, mathematicians, economists, pa=
leontologists, and many more. There is an uncanny resemblance between his f=
indings and my own. Moonshot founders, at their core, are audacious creativ=
es. They think independently and in exponential cadences, imaginatively and=
 in crystal-clear execution.=C2=A0
Second, I explored key philosophies that most, if not all, of the founders =
I spoke to share. Most agree that there is a moral imperative to make moons=
hots. They are personally fulfilled by their missions and antifragile again=
st failures. They employ mental models such as first principles thinking, s=
econd-order thinking, and systems thinking.=C2=A0
Take Lilac Solutions [https://substack.com/redirect/0685f77e-9df4-4314-8277=
-879f012c6df9?u=3D16283549], which realized that increasing lithium supply =
and mining rare earth metals sustainably allows EV manufacturers to build b=
etter batteries and thus electrify automobiles to mitigate climate change=
=E2=80=94a bottoms-up, first-principles-driven mission. When asked why he=
=E2=80=99s working on a battery supply chain company, founder David Snydack=
er said [https://substack.com/redirect/7bdf25a6-fd30-4596-b76f-1884dc69eaa9=
?u=3D16283549],
=E2=80=9CPersonally, the most rewarding moment for me has been delivering p=
ositive results to customers. As nerdy as this may sound, I care deeply abo=
ut the success of the lithium industry, and I want to do everything I can t=
o make a major contribution. For me, Lilac is a small part of something muc=
h bigger=E2=80=94the lithium battery industry=E2=80=94a relatively small in=
dustry today that carries the weight of a billion future cars and trucks on=
 its shoulders.=E2=80=9D
He=E2=80=99s doing it because it is necessary to the grand scheme of things=
=2E=C2=A0
Or Deepmind [https://substack.com/redirect/4890d318-6e8d-460d-87e3-5a7d1f58=
c2c1?u=3D16283549], an R&D lab that builds safe artificial intelligence sys=
tems. They know that AI, if used properly, can solve the grand protein fold=
ing problem (AlphaFold) and diagnose diseases faster than ever, which can r=
evolutionize drug discovery and bioinformatics as we know it (second-order =
thinking). But, they also know that AI can be used negatively for social pr=
oblems such as algorithmic biases to national security and bioterrorism (sy=
stems thinking). Ultimately, moonshot founders are wise. They know that fro=
ntier tech can be used for good and evil because =E2=80=9Cany sufficiently =
advanced technology is indistinguishable from magic,=E2=80=9D as Arthur C. =
Clarke says [https://substack.com/redirect/271e0866-8942-4a96-b259-14ee78b9=
e4ca?u=3D16283549].=C2=A0
Third, I highlight key strategies to get started on a deeptech company, fro=
m storytelling to hacking the urgency around global trends and issues. If I=
 had to pick the most interesting one, it would be deeptech investor Josh W=
olfe=E2=80=99s [https://substack.com/redirect/29843d89-fc94-441f-b1fa-f15ff=
859437e?u=3D16283549] framework on predicting the future: finding arrows of=
 progress [https://substack.com/redirect/273795a4-18e3-4459-b1e3-784752d17c=
20?u=3D16283549].=C2=A0
Wolfe=E2=80=99s popular example is that of the half-life of technological i=
ntimacy, which describes how technology is coming closer to humans ever so =
slightly as time goes on. We start with the giant ENIAC computer that took =
up the size of a room, then move to personal computers which sat on a deskt=
op, then laptops that we cradled on our laps, then phones in our pockets, t=
hen AirPods in our ears, then programmable contacts in your eyes, and so on=
=2E Soon, we=E2=80=99ll be able to perfor=
m mind control and near-telekinesis =
when interacting with tech (CTRL Labs [https://substack.com/redirect/1acc9e=
a2-9372-4a91-8cc2-1834151b6970?u=3D16283549]). A little further out, we=E2=
=80=99ll be able to interface directly with computers through our brains (N=
euralink [https://substack.com/redirect/af075917-e6d3-4f20-8bbf-e02777a31e7=
c?u=3D16283549]).
Sure, in hindsight, the magical seems obvious and even mundane. But during =
each step-change, no one knew how the products would fare. One thing that y=
ou could=E2=80=99ve done is bet on human nature=E2=80=94that things will be=
come broadly better, faster, cheaper, safer, and more efficient. Moonshots =
follow trends just like that=E2=80=94people will inevitably want faster tra=
vel from supersonic point-to-point suborbital transportation, cheaper drugs=
 and healthcare, and so much more.=C2=A0
Finally, I ended with what we must do to bolster the deeptech ecosystem, wh=
ich I define as startups, VC, academia, government, education, and media. I=
t all boils down to the simple framework in Joel Mokyr=E2=80=99s book, The =
Lever of Riches: Technological Creativity and Economic Progress [https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/7c4a9aa6-3663-46de-baac-12219f963456?u=3D16283549]. He =
says that to make progress, we must improve social infrastructure, incentiv=
es, and attitudes. People will take risks when they have a social safety ne=
t, when it=E2=80=99s in their favor, and when they=E2=80=99re in an encoura=
ging environment. When it comes to startups, this can mean providing a univ=
ersal basic income for scientists, giving tax benefits for R&D, and creatin=
g a cultural mindset similar to the one that united the nation around the A=
pollo Missions.=C2=A0
Scientific progress is human progress, and it takes a village to lift it up=
=2E We need a culture that celebrates and supports moonshots.=C2=A0
Part 4: The State of Deeptech
A lot has changed since I published my book in December 2020. During the re=
cent bull market, deeptech companies reached unprecedented valuations and h=
eights by taking advantage of cheap capital, newfound urgency, and motivate=
d talent. Many were lucky to raise cash before the downturn, which is fortu=
nate, because moonshot companies often need to support a heavy burn rate.=
=C2=A0
Today, cash needs are declining as deeptech enters the phase that software =
entered a decade ago: better infrastructure, declining costs, willing buyer=
s, and more public support. Founding costs are coming down (see: launching =
a space company with SpaceX), the government is a more willing buyer (see: =
Palantir and Anduril), and we=E2=80=99ve recently vibe-shifted into our Spu=
tnik moment=E2=80=94a realization that we=E2=80=99re falling behind on scie=
ntific productivity.=C2=A0
Fortunately, decades=E2=80=99 worth of effort across many of humanity=E2=80=
=99s hardest-to-solve challenges are bearing fruit at just the right time. =
Specifically, I=E2=80=99m excited by a few industry trends [https://substac=
k.com/redirect/0468ee1a-d3d3-483a-bdac-afa1224983fd?u=3D16283549]:=C2=A0
Space: launch costs per kg are exponentially decreasing [https://substack.c=
om/redirect/57c9bbca-b481-45bf-9538-fc74fff2fb85?u=3D16283549], thanks larg=
ely to SpaceX, enabling founders that are creating in a wide range of sub-s=
ectors such as space infrastructure (Privateer Space [https://substack.com/=
redirect/41d6739b-07ac-41b6-8971-4799553addb5?u=3D16283549]), logistics (At=
omos Space [https://substack.com/redirect/b6615b87-b132-439d-9e11-90a372bf5=
0d0?u=3D16283549], Firefly Aerospace [https://substack.com/redirect/d557a20=
a-20b4-459c-9309-cd8aeb7c5056?u=3D16283549], Venus Aerospace [https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/8af738d6-165b-4629-9882-5fd1e9382634?u=3D16283549], Epic A=
erospace [https://substack.com/redirect/6afb2c88-ade0-4beb-8d22-d6e384608a1=
9?u=3D16283549]), propulsion (Impulse Space [https://substack.com/redirect/=
4e37fb23-9196-4a3d-a1ac-1a988dd6186b?u=3D16283549]), computing (Cognitive S=
pace [https://substack.com/redirect/36b3ff3a-5612-4437-93f0-209f1fc68cb8?u=
=3D16283549]), manufacturing (Varda Space [https://substack.com/redirect/81=
db33d5-521d-40f8-80a5-1e458431892a?u=3D16283549], Inversion Space [https://=
substack.com/redirect/40db5934-6b93-45b1-aff2-472543dc0f51?u=3D16283549]), =
tourism (Space Perspective [https://substack.com/redirect/c61895dc-1a2f-460=
0-9725-206bae1fc153?u=3D16283549]), and more. There is also greater involve=
ment from the DoD and Space Force in nurturing some of these booming subsec=
tors.=C2=A0
2021 Total Funding: $9.1 billion+=C2=A0
Biotech: the cost of genome sequencing is also exponentially decreasing [ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/e13796bd-da6a-4e3b-825e-152731afb687?u=3D162835=
49], sparking advances in genetic engineering, drug discovery, and more. Ta=
ngentially, synthetic and computational biology are reaching new heights, a=
nd biotech tooling is becoming as accessible as any software product. Longe=
vity research has also recently boomed with newfound interest, talent, and =
capital (Loyal [https://substack.com/redirect/6f962e46-1bb5-4947-82d1-2d82c=
9f23047?u=3D16283549], Longevity Fund [https://substack.com/redirect/a35499=
a2-e690-4dc9-a8eb-e3dff083fc56?u=3D16283549], Fauna Bio [https://substack.c=
om/redirect/7e095dd5-a0be-40f9-9a5b-1519c513f90e?u=3D16283549]). Check out =
The Century of Biology [https://substack.com/redirect/36527568-76cb-4603-86=
9b-0e9968d1e055?u=3D16283549] for more=E2=80=94shoutout to Elliot on the No=
t Boring team!
2021 Total Funding: $144.6 billion+ in Life Sciences, $27.3 billion + in me=
dtech
Energy/Climate: We are coming closer to scaling nuclear power, from small m=
odular reactors (Radiant Energy, Marvel Fusion, Oklo, Zap Energy) to fusion=
 energy systems (Commonwealth Fusion). Renewable energy adoption is increas=
ingly dominating the market [https://substack.com/redirect/21305a34-4822-46=
83-a43a-7fbc31952142?u=3D16283549] relative to oil and gas.=C2=A0
Another key trend is the need for energy independence, as geopolitics conti=
nues to sour our globalized energy infrastructure and supply. Many such com=
panies are seeking to onshore this industry.=C2=A0
2021 Total Funding: $13.5 billion+
Advanced Manufacturing: the movement around American dynamism and onshoring=
 manufacturing follows similar sentiments as mentioned above, causing the h=
ardtech market to change due to pressure from increasing demand and geopoli=
tical uncertainty (Hadrian [https://substack.com/redirect/6ad2f37c-f60e-4ea=
e-a368-d15e3a9867b7?u=3D16283549]).=C2=A0
2021 Total Funding: $12.5 billion+, $16.9 billion+ in Semiconductors, $16.1=
 billion+ in Robotics/drones
Artificial Intelligence, Machine Learning, and Deep Learning algorithms con=
tinue to get more complex and adopted into everyday life. We made the title=
 image for this post with OpenAI=E2=80=99s DALL=E2=80=A2E 2. Deepmind even =
solved [https://substack.com/redirect/d24e2a00-d94e-4ef0-9879-3aa60ca6e2b7?=
u=3D16283549] the 60-year protein folding problem with deep learning. There=
 are countless more quotidian examples.=C2=A0
2021 Total Funding: $10.4 billion+
There has never been a better time to start a deeptech company, for a few r=
easons.=C2=A0
First, there=E2=80=99s an influx of new talent. Many want to put their func=
tional skills toward missions they align with, considering how their lives =
changed over COVID. Another major group is those pouring into the entrepren=
eurship scene from America=E2=80=99s robust academic environment. Many smar=
t people want to see their research be commercialized and are now taking ri=
sks to do it.=C2=A0
Second, there is a proliferation of capital, whether non-dilutive or diluti=
ve. In 2021, $3.8 billion [https://substack.com/redirect/64802e07-ac9d-42e6=
-8efd-09220e0d87f8?u=3D16283549] was granted in the form of SBIR/STTR grant=
s, and nearly $80 billion [https://substack.com/redirect/0468ee1a-d3d3-483a=
-bdac-afa1224983fd?u=3D16283549] in private VC money was invested into deep=
tech startups. These numbers are all exponential increases from previous ye=
ars.=C2=A0
Third, there is an improving safety net for founders to take on science-hea=
vy ideas, whether that means better startup ecosystems, resources, and inst=
itutions; the cross-pollination of ideas driven by remote work and social m=
edia; or standing on the shoulders of giants in the form of new labs, incub=
ators, accelerators, corporate R&D labs, and other foundries for risk-takin=
g.=C2=A0
Fourth, there=E2=80=99s proof that solving the hardest challenges can pay o=
ff. SpaceX is the United States=E2=80=99 most valuable private unicorn, wit=
h a $125 billion valuation. In addition to providing a platform for new spa=
ce companies, SpaceX provides inspiration for a new generation of deeptech =
entrepreneurs, like a modern day =E2=80=9CWe Choose to Go to the Moon=E2=80=
=9D speech.=C2=A0
Finally, there are large-scale experiments in metascience.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Over the past few years, a Cambrian explosion [https://substack.com/redirec=
t/1a72e677-7830-41ff-93b4-8a20cf2a1397?u=3D16283549] of new scientific orga=
nizations arose as scientists and funders pursued experiments outside of tr=
aditional academia. For those like Arcadia Science [https://substack.com/re=
direct/6c722687-69d9-427e-af8b-8ce97f4c65a0?u=3D16283549], it is to researc=
h hyper-specific frontiers of biotech. For those like New Science [https://=
substack.com/redirect/d97b7d48-910a-4d86-836c-a33c270838bd?u=3D16283549], i=
t=E2=80=99s to fund younger scientists pursuing bolder, long-term projects.=
 For those like Convergent Research [https://substack.com/redirect/ab6ba1c6=
-0357-4263-93fa-42456a33e124?u=3D16283549], it=E2=80=99s to galvanize a wel=
l-resourced group around a topic that doesn=E2=80=99t fit academic timeline=
s and requirements. Not to mention Arc Institute [https://substack.com/redi=
rect/8b182d96-d79a-44a4-b782-25e085d245d7?u=3D16283549], Astera [https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/91813193-004f-4b6e-a04f-6f3e4eed6840?u=3D16283549], Alt=
os Labs [https://substack.com/redirect/b14ed784-e811-4703-b3b4-2fc752b0ee8c=
?u=3D16283549], VitaDAO [https://substack.com/redirect/4e041e3a-cfc7-4990-a=
3bf-1f3e6599544f?u=3D16283549], and so many more that you can find in the O=
veredge Catalog [https://substack.com/redirect/6da9114b-2744-4ab0-a981-4ac5=
298dab4a?u=3D16283549], a compilation of these organizations by a mentor of=
 mine, Sam Arbesman [https://substack.com/redirect/49007b88-57c1-40a3-8798-=
4b89e15333e2?u=3D16283549].=C2=A0
This organizational experimentation is driven by a few factors, from new re=
search methods to forms of governance to multidisciplinary focuses. On the =
one hand, there are people with a lot of money who want to do some good wit=
h it. On the other, it's the growing realization that traditional academia =
is not favorable for everyone. The current grant system favors safer resear=
ch, older scientists, and greater credentials [https://substack.com/redirec=
t/4cad310f-c552-4cf8-b868-0df3baf8d6dc?u=3D16283549]. There is absolutely a=
n argument to be made for that. But, this is not ideal for the more enterpr=
ising scientists whose unconventional ideas don=E2=80=99t fit the pace and =
timescale of traditional research expectations.=C2=A0
When the average age of scientists who receive grant money is greater than =
40, you know the system doesn=E2=80=99t favor young people with fresh ideas=
=2E=C2=A0
Science is slow, messy, and human. But, we don=E2=80=99t have to stay const=
rained by the existing system. From DAOs [https://substack.com/redirect/8b6=
1fc66-8508-4f60-8391-4d493f88f500?u=3D16283549] to corporate R&D [https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/f71a81a6-9f6d-4739-8001-ca818d845918?u=3D16283549], pa=
tronage systems [https://substack.com/redirect/85ba7fb4-3925-43a7-8216-d947=
e1785062?u=3D16283549] to for-profit labs [https://substack.com/redirect/6c=
722687-69d9-427e-af8b-8ce97f4c65a0?u=3D16283549], we=E2=80=99re seeing rapi=
d iterations of what could be the new normal in metascience. The explicit e=
nd goal of the majority of these institutions is to commercialize the findi=
ngs and spin-out companies.=C2=A0
These new ways of funding, doing, and disseminating research have the poten=
tial to generate more of the fresh new ideas that deeptech companies thrive=
 on. Half a century ago, the government set the priorities, academia carrie=
d out the research, and government labs, working in partnership with privat=
e industry, executed on the top-down plan. Today, that flow is often revers=
ed. Bottoms-up research, in combination with traditional institutions, can =
point those entrepreneurs who want to build bottoms-up moonshots in new dir=
ections.
Whether it's for brain-computer interfaces (Kernal [https://substack.com/re=
direct/d838bdb5-0227-4443-8225-18cabe78c020?u=3D16283549], Neuralink [https=
://substack.com/redirect/af075917-e6d3-4f20-8bbf-e02777a31e7c?u=3D16283549]=
), national security (Anduril [https://substack.com/redirect/f891b189-f75b-=
4136-8755-043a19a3b144?u=3D16283549]), decarbonization (Twelve [https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/3c01e4d4-248f-4b4e-a78b-27477927a1c6?u=3D16283549]), hum=
an health in space (Ursa Bio [https://substack.com/redirect/83fe0867-f285-4=
15f-b984-055986ff0d07?u=3D16283549]), advanced manufacturing (Hadrian [http=
s://substack.com/redirect/6ad2f37c-f60e-4eae-a368-d15e3a9867b7?u=3D16283549=
]) or a plethora of other frontier tech industries, progress starts with fr=
esh ideas and individual effort.=C2=A0
The exciting and scary part about the shift from government-led moonshots t=
o startup-led moonshots is that this new model relies on the ambitions and =
efforts of individuals and small teams. I suspect many people who might bui=
ld in deeptech are reading this right now and that some of you are working =
on getting people to click ads. We're at a crucible moment. Markets are roi=
led. Layoffs are daily. People are suffering. And moonshots are needed more=
 than ever.=C2=A0
Luckily, the infrastructure and funding are there. The companies we've cove=
red are creating drafts of the blueprint. Today, unlike any time in history=
, you can turn your sci-fi fantasies into reality and find a willing market=
 for your ideas. We need to dream, sure, and then we need to build.
Let=E2=80=99s make some moonshots, through hardships and to the stars.
Per Aspera ad Astra.
Thanks to Rahul [https://substack.com/redirect/c6436659-9623-4d52-81c2-c541=
7e4125b7?u=3D16283549] for writing and inspiring, and to Dan [https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/1a29cf5b-aba9-4ed5-8e1c-5d8897467c74?u=3D16283549] for edi=
ting!
Thanks for reading, and see you on Monday,
Packy

