yle=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em =
0;">After decades of government-led scientific progress, the time has come =
for deeptech startups to lead the charge. These startups will lean on acade=
mic research and governments, tapping into their vast budgets and real need=
s. But the pieces are in place for deeptech startups to drive the innovatio=
n agenda.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height=
: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>My thesis: </span><strong>deeptech startu=
ps are just as important as academia to scientific progress.</strong></p><p=
 style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1=
em 0;">Research offers the foundational knowledge that startups scale to th=
e general public. We need both&#8212;academia and industry&#8212;there&#821=
7;s no question about it. But tracing back to World War II, one of the most=
 significant turning points in American ingenuity, public funding and direc=
tion were practically required for large-scale scientific progress. Today, =
America needs to lean on its competitive advantage&#8211;bottoms-up innovat=
ion&#8211;to win the next century.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; fon=
t-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">For the past 70 years,=
 when it came to deeptech and scientific progress, the government led,&#160=
; and then handed off to the public sector to commercialize technology beyo=
nd military applications. The Manhattan Project, for example, directly crea=
ted the atomic bomb and indirectly unlocked insights that made nuclear powe=
r possible. Today, nuclear is a crucial element of energy abundance and a p=
otent weapon in the fight against climate change. Ironically, the atomic bo=
mb could help save or destroy the planet.</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>Military R&amp;=
D around nuclear physics also advanced our understanding of biology with th=
e popularization of radioisotopes as treatments for </span><a href=3D"https=
://substack.com/redirect/c0a4327f-fca2-4fb4-8508-3b5e60ddb6b6?u=3D16283549"=
 rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">cancer, dia=
gnostics, and tools</a><span> for understanding metabolic pathways. War eff=
orts even birthed the first general-purpose computer, the ENIAC, by way of =
cryptography used to decipher German military codes.&#160;</span></p><div c=
