; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Kurion was prepar=
ed. It was one of a few companies selected to collaborate with various gove=
rnments and help contain the waste. In little time, they successfully desig=
ned, built, and delivered their technology to remove 68 million gallons of =
radioactive waste at a fraction of the previously perceived cost. It was a =
win for progress and a saving grace for people in Japan.&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"=
><span>Kurion is a story of defying the odds and fundamentally pushing forw=
ard our understanding of chemistry and physics. All done by a team of entre=
preneurs, bottoms-up. It would have been too late if the team had waited fo=
r the government to demand a solution. Ideate, innovate, </span><em>then</e=
m><span> sell. In the end, Kurion was </span><a href=3D"https://substack.co=
m/redirect/6a6938b6-0d5b-47b8-b019-fe4841bb8765?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" styl=
e=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">acquired</a><span> for $3=
50 million in 2016.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">We chase moonshots because the=
y fix inefficiencies, drive progress, and make money. They're still busines=
ses; both the technology and the economics need to work. But, the seemingly=
 impossible journey and real-world impact of it all is what makes them wort=
hy of the lunar metaphor.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 1=
6px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">I can keep going.&#160;</p><p s=
tyle=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em=
 0;">Imagine devoting your life&#8217;s work to unearthing a fairly complex=
 concept within neuroscience and even getting a principle named after you, =
then having that work almost entirely invalidated by a newcomer to the spac=
e.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;=
 margin: 0 0 1em 0;">That sucks.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-=
size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>This is exactly wh=
at happened to neurophysiologist </span><strong>Elwood Henneman</strong><sp=
an>. The Henneman Size Principle states that in motor recruitment, the neur=
ons that control muscles act in groups according to the magnitude of the fo=
rce needed for an action. Essentially, it was believed you could not turn i=
ndividual neurons on or off, that you can only fire off a group of them wit=
h the number determined by a movement&#8217;s strength.&#160;</span></p><p =
style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1e=
m 0;"><span>Founder </span><strong>Thomas Reardon</strong><span> and his te=
am at </span><strong>CTRL Labs</strong><span> </span><a href=3D"https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/7417ab68-89f9-4285-bfa1-6eea53f34d4c?u=3D16283549" rel=
=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">disproved that =
principle</a><span> by building a noninvasive hardware solution that connec=
ts one&#8217;s nervous system to a computer or machine&#8212;effectively al=
lowing a user to control the machine with an intent to act. Upon isolating =
each fired neuron, the signal that would go to a muscle can be translated a=
nd expressed on a brain-computer interface. Yes, CTRL Labs made mind-contro=
l a reality.</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-he=
ight: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Think of the Force in Star Wars. By merely =
thinking about a certain action, those who can wield the Force can control =
an external entity&#8212;whether it&#8217;s an object or an entire person. =
Reardon figured out a way to &#8220;escape the boundaries of your body&#822=
1; by fundamentally granting a user more control over their life.&#160;</p>=
<p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 1em 0;"><span>His </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/d171c5cc=
-f5e8-4fde-8c5b-726f22a2a565?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a=
; text-decoration: underline;">motivation</a><span>?&#160;</span></p><block=
quote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1em 0;"><p style=3D"=
color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; marg=
in-left: 1em;"><em>I&#8217;m working on human happiness. I&#8217;m working =
on empowering people. I&#8217;m working on giving people new, extraordinary=
 abilities... I didn&#8217;t want to create technology that was for 100,000=
 people or a million people. I wanted to create technology that was for 8 b=
illion people.</em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>While he wants to prove =
the &#8220;impossible&#8221; is possible and build a high-leverage project,=
 Reardon&#8217;s motivating force is giving people autonomy. That&#8217;s q=
uite fitting, considering that </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redir=
ect/64840123-2675-400d-965d-1ae103d72bb4?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"co=
lor: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">he made Internet Explorer in the=
 1990s</a><span>. He knows how to impact and empower a billion people&#8212=
;in typical moonshot fashion. It&#8217;s also worth noting that only four y=
ears after its founding in 2015, Facebook acquired CTRL Labs for $1 billion=
=2E In the 2021 event, </span><em><a href=
