-9879-3aa60ca6e2b7?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-dec=
oration: underline;">solved</a><span> the 60-year protein folding problem w=
ith deep learning. There are countless more quotidian examples.&#160;</span=
></p><ul style=3D"margin-top: 0;"><li style=3D"margin-bottom: 4px; margin-l=
eft: 8px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 4px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p=
 style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; ma=
rgin-bottom: 0;"><strong>2021 Total Funding</strong><span>: $10.4 billion+<=
/span></p></li></ul></li></ul><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">There has never been a better time t=
o start a deeptech company, for a few reasons.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: =
#1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>Firs=
t, there&#8217;s an influx of </span><strong>new talent</strong><span>. Man=
y want to put their functional skills toward missions they align with, cons=
idering how their lives changed over COVID. Another major group is those po=
uring into the entrepreneurship scene from America&#8217;s robust academic =
environment. Many smart people want to see their research be commercialized=
 and are now taking risks to do it.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1=
a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>Second, =
there is a </span><strong>proliferation of capital</strong><span>, whether =
non-dilutive or dilutive. In 2021, </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/r=
edirect/52904b79-3ef6-41ba-b456-61e24a732ab2?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=
=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">$3.8 billion</a><span> was=
 granted in the form of SBIR/STTR grants, and </span><a href=3D"https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/0468ee1a-d3d3-483a-bdac-afa1224983fd?u=3D16283549" rel=
=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">nearly $80 bill=
ion</a><span> in private VC money was invested into deeptech startups. Thes=
e numbers are all exponential increases from previous years.&#160;</span></=
p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 1em 0;"><span>Third, there is an </span><strong>improving safety net</st=
rong><span> for founders to take on science-heavy ideas, whether that means=
 better startup ecosystems, resources, and institutions; the cross-pollinat=
ion of ideas driven by remote work and social media; or standing on the sho=
ulders of giants in the form of new labs, incubators, accelerators, corpora=
te R&amp;D labs, and other foundries for risk-taking.&#160;</span></p><p st=
yle=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em =
0;"><span>Fourth, there&#8217;s </span><strong>proof that solving the harde=
st challenges can pay off</strong><span>. SpaceX is the United States&#8217=
; most valuable private unicorn, with a $125 billion valuation. In addition=
 to providing a platform for new space companies, SpaceX provides inspirati=
on for a new generation of deeptech entrepreneurs, like a modern day &#8220=
;We Choose to Go to the Moon&#8221; speech.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"col=
or: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>=
Finally, there are large-scale </span><strong>experiments in metascience</s=
trong><span>.&#160;&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>Over the past few years,=
 a </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/1a72e677-7830-41ff-93b4-=
8a20cf2a1397?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoratio=
n: underline;">Cambrian explosion</a><span> of new scientific organizations=
 arose as scientists and funders </span><strong>pursued experiments outside=
 of traditional academia</strong><span>. For those like </span><strong><a h=
ref=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/6c722687-69d9-427e-af8b-8ce97f4c65a0?u=
=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;"=
>Arcadia Science</a></strong><span>, it is to research hyper-specific front=
iers of biotech. For those like </span><strong><a href=3D"https://substack.=
com/redirect/d97b7d48-910a-4d86-836c-a33c270838bd?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" st=
yle=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">New Science</a></strong=
><span>, it&#8217;s to fund younger scientists pursuing bolder, long-term p=
rojects. For those like </span><strong><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redi=
rect/ab6ba1c6-0357-4263-93fa-42456a33e124?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"c=
olor: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">Convergent Research</a></strong=
><span>, it&#8217;s to galvanize a well-resourced group around a topic that=
 doesn&#8217;t fit academic timelines and requirements. Not to mention </sp=
an><strong><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/8b182d96-d79a-44a4-b782=
-25e085d245d7?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decorati=
on: underline;">Arc Institute</a></strong><span>, </span><strong><a href=3D=
"https://substack.com/redirect/91813193-004f-4b6e-a04f-6f3e4eed6840?u=3D162=
83549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">Aster=
a</a></strong><span>, </span><strong><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redire=
ct/b14ed784-e811-4703-b3b4-2fc752b0ee8c?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"col=
or: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">Altos Labs</a></strong><span>, </=
span><strong><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/4e041e3a-cfc7-4990-a3=
bf-1f3e6599544f?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decora=
tion: underline;">VitaDAO</a></strong><span>, and so many more that you can=
 find in the </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/6da9114b-2744-=
4ab0-a981-4ac5298dab4a?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text=
-decoration: underline;">Overedge Catalog</a><span>, a compilation of these=
 organizations by a mentor of mine, </span><strong><a href=3D"https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/49007b88-57c1-40a3-8798-4b89e15333e2?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"=
" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">Sam Arbesman</a></s=
trong><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>This organizational experiment=
ation is driven by a few factors, from new research methods to forms of gov=
ernance to multidisciplinary focuses. On the one hand, there are people wit=
h a lot of money who want to do some good with it. On the other, it's the g=
rowing realization that traditional academia is not favorable for everyone.=
 The current grant system favors safer research, </span><a href=3D"https://=
substack.com/redirect/4cad310f-c552-4cf8-b868-0df3baf8d6dc?u=3D16283549" re=
l=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">older scientis=
ts, and greater credentials</a><span>. There is absolutely an argument to b=
e made for that. But, this is not ideal for the more enterprising scientist=
s whose unconventional ideas don&#8217;t fit the pace and timescale of trad=
itional research expectations.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; =
font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">When the average ag=
e of scientists who receive grant money is greater than 40, you know the sy=
stem doesn&#8217;t favor young people with fresh ideas.&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"=
><span>Science is slow, messy, and human. But, we don&#8217;t have to stay =
constrained by the existing system. From </span><a href=3D"https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/8b61fc66-8508-4f60-8391-4=
d493f88f500?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" s=
tyle=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">DAOs</a><span> to </sp=
an><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/f71a81a6-9f6d-4739-8001-ca818d8=
45918?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: unde=
rline;">corporate R&amp;D</a><span>, </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com=
/redirect/85ba7fb4-3925-43a7-8216-d947e1785062?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=
=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">patronage systems</a><span=
> to </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/6c722687-69d9-427e-af8=
b-8ce97f4c65a0?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decorat=
ion: underline;">for-profit labs</a><span>, we&#8217;re seeing rapid iterat=
ions of what could be the new normal in metascience. The explicit end goal =
of the majority of these institutions is to commercialize the findings and =
spin-out companies.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">These new ways of funding, doi=
ng, and disseminating research have the potential to generate more of the f=
resh new ideas that deeptech companies thrive on. Half a century ago, the g=
overnment set the priorities, academia carried out the research, and govern=
ment labs, working in partnership with private industry, executed on the to=
p-down plan. Today, that flow is often reversed. Bottoms-up research, in co=
mbination with traditional institutions, can point those entrepreneurs who =
want to build bottoms-up moonshots in new directions.</p><p style=3D"color:=
 #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>Whe=
ther it's for brain-computer interfaces (</span><strong><a href=3D"https://=
substack.com/redirect/d838bdb5-0227-4443-8225-18cabe78c020?u=3D16283549" re=
l=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">Kernal</a></st=
rong><span>, </span><strong><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/af0759=
17-e6d3-4f20-8bbf-e02777a31e7c?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a=
1a; text-decoration: underline;">Neuralink</a></strong><span>), national se=
curity (</span><strong><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/f891b189-f7=
5b-4136-8755-043a19a3b144?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; t=
ext-decoration: underline;">Anduril</a></strong><span>), decarbonization (<=
/span><strong><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/3c01e4d4-248f-4b4e-a=
78b-27477927a1c6?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decor=
ation: underline;">Twelve</a></strong><span>), human health in space (</spa=
n><strong><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/83fe0867-f285-415f-b984-=
055986ff0d07?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoratio=
n: underline;">Ursa Bio</a></strong><span>), advanced manufacturing (</span=
><strong><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/6ad2f37c-f60e-4eae-a368-d=
15e3a9867b7?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration=
: underline;">Hadrian</a></strong><span>) or a plethora of other frontier t=
ech industries, progress starts with fresh ideas and individual effort.&#16=
0;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">The exciting and scary part about the shift from gove=
rnment-led moonshots to startup-led moonshots is that this new model relies=
 on the ambitions and efforts of individuals and small teams. I suspect man=
y people who might build in deeptech are reading this right now and that so=
me of you are working on getting people to click ads. We're at a crucible m=
oment. Markets are roiled. Layoffs are daily. People are suffering. And moo=
nshots are needed more than ever.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font=
-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Luckily, the infrastruc=
ture and funding are there. The companies we've covered are creating drafts=
 of the blueprint. Today, unlike any time in history, you can turn your sci=
-fi fantasies into reality and find a willing market for your ideas. We nee=
d to dream, sure, and then we need to build.</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a;=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Let&#8217;s make s=
ome moonshots, through hardships and to the stars.</p><p style=3D"color: #1=
